INSERT INTO articles (title, created_at, updated_at, body) values ('Apparent magnitude', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, '[[File:65Cyb-LB3-apmag.jpg|thumb|350px|right|Asteroid [[65 Cybele]] and two stars, with their magnitudes labeled]]

The ''''''apparent magnitude'''''' (''''''''''m'''''''''') of a celestial body is a measure of its [[brightness]] as seen by an observer on [[Earth]], adjusted to the value it would have in the absence of the [[Earth''s atmosphere|atmosphere]]. The brighter the object appears, the lower the value of its [[Magnitude (astronomy)|magnitude]]. Generally the [[visible spectrum]] (vmag) is used as a basis for the apparent magnitude, but other regions of the spectrum, such as the [[near-infrared]] [[J-band]], are also used. In the visible spectrum [[Sirius]] is the brightest star in the night sky, while in the near-infrared J-band, [[Betelgeuse]] is the brightest.

