The ''''''Book of Daniel'''''' is one of the books of the [[Hebrew Bible]] and the Christian [[Old Testament]]. It is notable for its changes from [[Biblical Hebrew|Hebrew]] to [[Biblical Aramaic|Aramaic]] and back. The first part of the book, comprising six chapters, is the story of [[Daniel]] set in the courts of [[Neo-Babylonian Empire|Babylonian]] and [[Achaemenid Empire]] during the time of the [[Babylonian captivity]]. The remainder of the book contain three [[Vision (spirituality)|visions]] and their interpretation.

There is sharp difference between the [[fundamentalism|fundamentalist]] view of Daniel and the [[scholarly consensus]]. Conservative Biblical scholars and evangelical commentators hold that its stories tell of real events and real [[prophecy|prophecies]] written during and shortly after the [[Babylonian captivity]] by a real [[Daniel]] living in the late sixth century BCE. The scholarly consensus is that the Book of Daniel (or at least the last three chapters) was written after [[Antiochus IV Epiphanes]] desecrated the altar of the Temple of Jerusalem around 167 BCE. In this view, Daniel was written in reaction to that incident and the final [[redaction]] of the work dates to the second century BCE. For secular scholars, the issue was settled over a century ago,{{sfn|Collins|2001|p=2}} but many Christians do not accept this line of reasoning, looking to [[Jesus]]'' implicit approval of the book by quoting from it in his teachings.

