INSERT INTO articles (title, created_at, updated_at, body) values ('Transport in Chad', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, '{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}
{{refimprove|date=August 2012}}

Transport infrastructure within [[Chad]] is generally poor, especially in the north and east of the country.  River transport is limited to the south-west corner. As of 2011 Chad had no railways though two lines are planned - from the capital to the Sudanese and Cameroonish borders.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}

Roads are mostly unsurfaced and are likely to be impassable during the [[wet season]], especially in the southern half of the country.  In the north, roads are merely tracks across the [[desert]] and [[land mines]] continue to present a danger.  Draft animals ([[horse]]s, [[donkey]]s and [[camel]]s) remain important in much of the country.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}

Fuel supplies can be erratic, even in the south-west of the country, and are expensive.  Elsewhere they are practically non-existent.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}

[[Image:Rebuilt bridge on Bragoto River.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Rebuilt Bridge in south west of Chad]]

