==Do calendars really measure time?==

I think a lot of misconceptions about calendars arise from the idea that a calendar measures time, like a clock or like a ruler measures distance.

All known calendars work by naming days (This is the definition in the Nupedia article). As such, a calendar can not measure time more accurately than 1 day. 
Furthermore, the duration of the day is known to vary in time owing to change in Earth''s rotation rate, so is not a good standard in time measurement.

A [[:solar calendar|solar calendar]] may measure years, by virtue of the fact that its year runs close to the cycle of seasons, but more accurate measurement can be got from an [[:ephemeris|ephemeris]]. 

The [[:year|year]] even when measured in SI [[:second|second]]s, varies in duration and so can not be considered a unit of the same time that measured by SI seconds.

