INSERT INTO articles (title, created_at, updated_at, body) values ('Craps', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, '[[Image:craps.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Example of playing dice used in craps]]
''''''Craps'''''' is a [[dice game]] in which the players make [[Gambling|wagers]] on the outcome of the roll, or a series of rolls, of a pair of dice. Players may wager money against each other (street craps, also known as shooting dice or rolling dice) or a bank ([[casino]] craps, also known as table craps).  Because it requires little equipment, street craps can be played in informal settings.

==History==
Craps developed from a simplification of the early English game of [[Hazard (game)|hazard]]. Its origins are complex and may date to the [[Crusades]], later being influenced by French gamblers.  What was to become the modern American version of the game was brought to [[New Orleans]] by [[Bernard de Marigny|Bernard Xavier Philippe de Marigny de Mandeville]], [[kinship|scion]] of wealthy [[Louisiana]] landowners, a gambler, and politician.')
