INSERT INTO articles (title, created_at, updated_at, body) values ('Fire (classical element)', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, '{{classic element}}
''''''[[Fire]]'''''' has been an important part of all [[culture]]s and [[religion]]s from pre-history to modern day and was vital to the development of civilization. It has been regarded in many different contexts throughout history, but especially as a metaphysical constant of the world.

==Greek and Roman tradition==
Fire is one of the four [[classical element]]s in ancient [[Greek philosophy]] and science.  It was commonly associated with the qualities of energy, assertiveness, and passion.  In one Greek myth, [[Prometheus]] stole ''''fire'''' from the gods to protect the otherwise helpless humans, but was punished for this charity.')
INSERT INTO articles (title, created_at, updated_at, body) values ('Air (classical element)', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, '{{classic element}}
''''''Air'''''' is often seen as a universal power or pure substance. Its supposed fundamental importance to life can be seen in words such as ''''aspire'''', ''''inspire'''', ''''perspire'''' and ''''spirit'''', all derived from the [[Latin]] ''''spirare''''.

==Greek and Roman tradition==
Air is one of the four [[classical element]]s in ancient [[Greek philosophy]] and science.  According to [[Plato]], it is associated with the [[octahedron]]; air is considered to be both hot and wet. The ancient Greeks used two words for air: ''''aer'''' meant the dim lower atmosphere, and ''''[[aether (mythology)|aether]]'''' meant the bright upper atmosphere above the clouds.')
INSERT INTO articles (title, created_at, updated_at, body) values ('Water (classical element)', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, '{{about|the philosophical [[classical element|element]]|the [[chemical substance]]|Water}}
{{classic element}}
''''''Water'''''' is one of the [[classical element|elements]] in [[Pre-Socratics|ancient Greek philosophy]], in the [[India|Asian Indian]] system ''''[[Classical element#Classical elements in Hinduism|Panchamahabhuta]]'''', and in the [[China|Chinese]] cosmological and [[Traditional Chinese Medicine|physiological]] system ''''[[Wu Xing]]''''. In contemporary [[esotericism|esoteric traditions]], it is commonly associated with the qualities of [[emotion]] and [[Intuition (knowledge)|intuition]].

==Greek and Roman tradition==
Water was one of many  ''''archai'''' proposed by the Pre-socratics, most of whom tried to reduce all things to a single substance. However, [[Empedocles]] of Acragas (c. 495-c. 435 BC) selected four archai for his four roots: [[Air (classical element)|air]], [[Fire (classical element)|fire]], water and [[Earth (classical element)|earth]]. Empedocles roots became the four classical elements of Greek philosophy. [[Plato]] (427-347 BC) took over the four elements of Empedocles. In the [[Timaeus (dialogue)|Timaeus]], his major cosmological dialogue, the [[Platonic solid]] associated with water is the [[icosahedron]] which is formed from twenty equilateral triangles. This makes water the element with the greatest number of sides, which Plato regarded as appropriate because water flows out of one''s hand when picked up, as if it is made of tiny little balls.')
