INSERT INTO articles (title, created_at, updated_at, body) values ('English in the Commonwealth of Nations', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'The use of the [[English language]] in most [[List of members of the Commonwealth of Nations|member countries]] of the [[Commonwealth of Nations]] was inherited from [[British Empire|British colonisation]]. English is spoken as a first or second language in most of the Commonwealth. In a few countries, such as [[Cyprus]] and [[Malaysia]], it does not have [[official language|official status]], but is widely used as a [[lingua franca]]. [[Mozambique]] is an exception - although English is widely spoken there, it is a former Portuguese colony which joined the Commonwealth in 1996.

Many regions, notably [[Canadian English|Canada]], [[Australian English|Australia]], [[Indian English|India]], [[New Zealand English|New Zealand]], [[South African English|South Africa]], [[Malaysian English|Malaysia]], [[Brunei English|Brunei]], [[Singapore English|Singapore]] and the [[Caribbean English|Caribbean]], have developed their own native varieties of the language. As such, generalisations cannot be made about the various forms of English used by the various member nations of the Commonwealth.

Written English as used in the Commonwealth generally favours [[American and British English spelling differences|British as opposed to American spelling]], with some exceptions in [[Canadian English|Canada]], where there is a strong influence from neighboring [[American English]], as well as in [[Australian English|Australia]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2013}}

The report of the Inter-Governmental Group on Criteria for Commonwealth Membership states that English is a symbol of Commonwealth heritage and unity.{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}}

== Native varieties ==
[[Southern Hemisphere]] native varieties of English began to develop during the 18th century, with the colonisation of Australasia and South Africa. [[Australian English]] and [[New Zealand English]] are closely related to each other, and share some similarities with [[South African English]]. The vocabularies of these dialects draw from both [[British English|British]] and [[American English]] as well as numerous native peculiarities.

[[Canadian English]] is a variety of [[North American English]]. It shares the same roots as the English of the United States because it was based on the immigration of [[British Loyalist]]s fleeing the [[American Revolution]] in the late eighteenth century{{Citation needed|date=July 2012}}. It was also influenced by Scottish, Irish and English immigration after the [[War of 1812]]. While the language has continued to change in all of these places{{Clarify|date=July 2012}}, modern Canadian English has inherited significant vocabulary and spelling from the shared political and social institutions of Commonwealth countries.

