In computing, ''''''multitasking'''''' is a method where multiple tasks, also known as [[Computer process|processes]], are performed during the same period of time. The tasks share common processing resources, such as a [[Central processing unit|CPU]] and main memory. In the case of a computer with a single CPU, only one task is said to be ''''running'''' at any point in time, meaning that the CPU is actively executing instructions for that task.
Multitasking solves the problem by [[Scheduling (computing)|scheduling]] which task may be the one running at any given time, and when another waiting task gets a turn.  The act of reassigning a CPU from one task to another one is called a [[context switch]].
When context switches occur frequently enough the illusion of [[Parallel computing|parallelism]] is achieved.
