INSERT INTO articles (title, created_at, updated_at, body) values ('Politics of the Cook Islands', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, '{{Politics of the Cook Islands}}
The ''''''politics of the Cook Islands'''''', an [[associated state]], takes place in a framework of a [[Parliamentary system|parliamentary]] [[representative democracy]] within a [[constitutional monarchy]]. The [[Monarchy in New Zealand|Queen of New Zealand]], represented in the Cook Islands by the [[Queen''s Representative]], is the [[Head of State]]; the Chief Minister is the [[head of government]] and of a  [[multi-party system]]. The Islands are self-governing in free association with [[New Zealand]] and are fully responsible for internal affairs. New Zealand retains some responsibility for external affairs, in consultation with the Cook Islands. In recent years, the Cook Islands has taken on more of its own external affairs; as of 2005, it has diplomatic relations in its own name with eighteen other countries. [[Executive power]] is exercised by the government, while [[legislative power]] is vested in both the government and [[Parliament of the Cook Islands|the islands'' parliament]].  The [[judiciary]] is independent of the executive and the legislatures.

==Constitution==
The [[Constitution of the Cook Islands]] took effect on August 4, 1965, when the Cook Islands became a [[Self-government|self-governing]] territory in [[Associated state|free association]] with [[New Zealand]]. The anniversary of these events in 1965 is commemorated annually on [[Constitution Day]], with week long activities known as ''''Te Maevea Nui Celebrations'''' locally.

