INSERT INTO articles (title, created_at, updated_at, body) values ('Demiurge', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, '{{God}}
The ''''''demiurge'''''' is a concept from the [[Platonism|Platonic]], [[Neopythagorean]], [[Middle Platonism|Middle Platonic]], and [[Neoplatonism|Neoplatonic]] schools of philosophy for an artisan-like figure responsible for the fashioning and maintenance of the physical universe. The term was subsequently adopted by the [[Gnosticism|Gnostics]]. Although a fashioner, the demiurge is not necessarily thought of as being the same as the creator figure in the familiar [[monotheism|monotheistic]] sense, because both the demiurge itself plus the material from which the demiurge fashions the universe are considered either uncreated and eternal, or the product of some other being, depending on the system. In Gnosticism the Demiurge, creator of the material world, was not God but the Archon.')
