INSERT INTO articles (title, created_at, updated_at, body) values ('Equivalence class', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, '{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}
:''''This article is about equivalency in [[mathematics]]; for equivalency in [[music]] see [[equivalence class (music)]].''''

In [[mathematics]], given a [[Set (mathematics)|set]] {{mvar|X}} and an [[equivalence relation]] {{math|~}} on {{mvar|X}}, the ''''''equivalence class'''''' of an element {{mvar|n}} in {{mvar|X}} is the [[subset]] of all elements in {{mvar|X}} which are equivalent to {{mvar|n}}. Equivalence classes among elements of a structure are often used to produce a smaller structure whose elements are the classes, distilling a relationship every element of the class shares with at least one other element of another class. This is known as ''''''[[Modulo (jargon)|modding out]]'''''' by the class. The class may assume the identity of one of the original elements, as when fractions are put in [[Irreducible fraction|reduced form]].

==Notation and formal definition==
An equivalence relation is a [[binary relation]] {{math|~}} satisfying three properties:
*For every element {{mvar|a}} in {{mvar|X}}, {{math|''''a'''' ~ ''''a''''}} ([[Reflexive relation|reflexivity]]),
*For every two elements {{mvar|a}} and {{mvar|b}} in {{mvar|X}}, if {{math|''''a'''' ~ ''''b''''}}, then {{math|''''b'''' ~ ''''a''''}} ([[Symmetric relation|symmetry]])
*For every three elements {{mvar|a}}, {{mvar|b}}, and {{mvar|c}} in {{mvar|X}}, if {{math|''''a'''' ~ ''''b''''}} and {{math|''''b'''' ~ ''''c''''}}, then {{math|''''a'''' ~ ''''c''''}} ([[Transitive relation|transitivity]]).

